# docling Best Practices

This document outlines best practices for utilizing Docling effectively in Python projects, particularly for OCR and document parsing. By adhering to these guidelines, you will optimize your code organization, improve performance, and enhance the reliability of your document processing applications.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use a Modular Approach
Organize your code into modules that reflect the functionality of your application. This makes it easier to maintain and test.

❌ BAD
```python
# all code in a single file
def process_document(doc):
    # processing logic
    pass

def extract_data(doc):
    # extraction logic
    pass
```

✅ GOOD
```python
# structure your project like this
# my_project/
# ├── main.py
# ├── processor.py
# └── extractor.py

# processor.py
def process_document(doc):
    # processing logic
    pass

# extractor.py
def extract_data(doc):
    # extraction logic
    pass
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Prefer Context Managers for Resource Management
Always use context managers when dealing with file I/O to ensure resources are properly managed.

❌ BAD
```python
file = open('document.pdf', 'rb')
data = file.read()
file.close()
```

✅ GOOD
```python
with open('document.pdf', 'rb') as file:
    data = file.read()
```

## Performance Considerations

### Optimize OCR Engine Selection
Choose the right OCR engine based on your document type. For multilingual documents, use EasyOCR; for high-speed processing, use RapidOCR.

❌ BAD
```python
from docling import OCR

ocr = OCR(engine='tesseract')  # Not ideal for speed
```

✅ GOOD
```python
from docling import OCR

ocr = OCR(engine='rapidocr')  # Best for speed and efficiency
```

### Enable Hardware Acceleration
If your environment supports it, enable hardware acceleration to improve OCR performance significantly.

✅ GOOD
```python
ocr = OCR(engine='rapidocr', use_gpu=True)  # Enable GPU for faster processing
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Misalignment in Table Extraction
Verify table boundary detection to prevent misalignment of columns, especially in multi-column formats.

❌ BAD
```python
data = extract_data(doc)  # May lead to misaligned columns
```

✅ GOOD
```python
data = extract_data(doc, verify_table_boundaries=True)  # Ensures accurate extraction
```

## Conclusion
By following these best practices, you will enhance the performance, reliability, and maintainability of your Docling-based applications. Always remember to choose the right tools for your specific use case and keep your code organized and well-tested.
